<p><b>Comparative mythology</b> is the comparison of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myth" title="Myth">myths</a> from different cultures in an attempt to identify shared themes and characteristics.<sup id="cite_ref-Littleton_32_1-0" class="reference"><a href="Comparative_mythology#cite_note-Littleton_32-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Comparative mythology has served a variety of academic purposes. For example, scholars have used the relationships between different myths to trace the development of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religions</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Culture" title="Culture">cultures</a>, to propose common origins for myths from different cultures, and to support various <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychology" title="Psychology">psychological theories</a>.
</p>
